00:41:18.140 --> 00:41:21.530
So you know, I mean,
development of AI i

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:26.510
would not place on small
cooperatives, right?

00:41:26.510 --> 00:41:29.810
But even in that discussion, it
would be interesting to see--

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:31.520
and there are
already cooperatives

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:36.680
that actually contribute to
the research of AI companies.

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:38.824
They are not doing
it themselves,

00:41:38.824 --> 00:41:40.240
but they are part
of this picture.

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:42.732
They're trying to insert
themselves in there.

00:41:42.732 --> 00:41:43.940
That was your first question.

00:41:43.940 --> 00:41:45.712
But then you had the second one?

00:41:45.712 --> 00:41:46.420
AUDIENCE: Oh, no.

00:41:46.420 --> 00:41:47.660
That was kind of my--

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:48.350
TREBOR SCHOLZ: Yeah, yeah.

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:49.683
No, I completely agree with you.

00:41:49.683 --> 00:41:52.670
And this is why areas, for
example, like, you know,

00:41:52.670 --> 00:41:54.640
home health care,
like I say it again.

00:41:54.640 --> 00:42:00.420
You know, we saw it being very
successful in the Netherlands,

00:42:00.420 --> 00:42:04.520
you know, where basically groups
of nurses form cooperatives,

00:42:04.520 --> 00:42:10.550
create websites with services
like prenatal care for Latino

00:42:10.550 --> 00:42:11.420
women.

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:12.920
You know, there's
this [INAUDIBLE],,

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:15.890
for example, done here
in Southern California

00:42:15.890 --> 00:42:19.910
where these nurses traditionally
through temp agencies

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:22.730
would pay 50% to
the temp agency.

00:42:22.730 --> 00:42:25.040
And now they have a
very different situation

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:28.700
when they run their own
operation like that.

00:42:28.700 --> 00:42:32.810
So there are clear advantages
for particular groups I think.

00:42:32.810 --> 00:42:33.765
So, yeah.

00:42:33.765 --> 00:42:35.390
AUDIENCE: One other
different question.

00:42:35.390 --> 00:42:38.750
You kind of mentioned that
there would be this ideal co-op

00:42:38.750 --> 00:42:39.787
platform kernel.

00:42:39.787 --> 00:42:40.620
TREBOR SCHOLZ: Yeah.

00:42:40.620 --> 00:42:43.121
AUDIENCE: And we make platforms
here a little bit sometimes.

00:42:43.121 --> 00:42:44.661
TREBOR SCHOLZ: I've
heard about that.

00:42:44.661 --> 00:42:45.350
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:42:45.350 --> 00:42:47.630
What kind of main
features do you

00:42:47.630 --> 00:42:49.910
think would exist in
this type of platform?

00:42:49.910 --> 00:42:50.993
TREBOR SCHOLZ: Absolutely.

00:42:50.993 --> 00:42:54.110
Well, it's really
for apps, right?

00:42:54.110 --> 00:42:59.000
Well, it's one worker
facing, one client facing,

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.110
for iOS and for Android.

00:43:01.110 --> 00:43:03.560
So it's really like four apps
that you would have to demo

00:43:03.560 --> 00:43:04.550
and have to develop.

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:09.160
And then they would have to
plug into different applications

00:43:09.160 --> 00:43:10.190
locally, right?

00:43:10.190 --> 00:43:14.480
So it would just be the
kernel, and then local.

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:17.000
So you know, it would
be somebody [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:18.650
what you would
consider small grant,

00:43:18.650 --> 00:43:22.150
I would consider an
enormous grant for this.

00:43:22.150 --> 00:43:24.350
And so we tried to
make a dent in that

00:43:24.350 --> 00:43:28.650
and actually hope to have this
done in the next two years.

00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:31.122
So I mean, if any of you
are interested in this

00:43:31.122 --> 00:43:33.080
and think that they would
like to support this,

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:35.450
we would, of course,
highly welcome that.

00:43:35.450 --> 00:43:39.987
AUDIENCE: I had a question
about policy changes--

00:43:39.987 --> 00:43:40.820
TREBOR SCHOLZ: Yeah.

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:44.210
AUDIENCE: --that could
encourage more co-ops or level

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:47.510
the playing field or take
a holistic approach to--

00:43:47.510 --> 00:43:49.810
TREBOR SCHOLZ: Absolutely.

00:43:49.810 --> 00:43:53.510
AUDIENCE: --creating, you know,
a world that results in more

00:43:53.510 --> 00:43:55.034
co-ops or whatever
that would be--

00:43:55.034 --> 00:43:56.200
TREBOR SCHOLZ: No, absolute.

00:43:56.200 --> 00:43:56.910
AUDIENCE: --if people
are thinking about that

00:43:56.910 --> 00:43:57.890
or if you have anything
to say about that.

00:43:57.890 --> 00:43:58.723
TREBOR SCHOLZ: Yeah.

00:43:58.723 --> 00:44:01.880
No, so part of what this
organization, the PCC,

00:44:01.880 --> 00:44:04.160
the Platform Cooperatives
and Consortium does

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:06.065
is we write policy
briefs for senators.

00:44:09.020 --> 00:44:14.780
And I don't know, in October,
we talked to the G7 about this.

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:17.630
And you know, we wrote
one for Kirsten Gillibrand

00:44:17.630 --> 00:44:19.190
who requested one.

00:44:19.190 --> 00:44:21.380
Because Kirsten Gillibrand
and Bernie Sanders

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:26.900
created this package on May 11,
I think, they released that,

00:44:26.900 --> 00:44:32.910
where they proposed a large
push for cooperatives.

00:44:32.910 --> 00:44:37.400
And so I think the
interventions are mostly

00:44:37.400 --> 00:44:39.180
on the municipal level, right?

00:44:39.180 --> 00:44:44.480
I wouldn't have all too much
hope on the federal level

00:44:44.480 --> 00:44:49.040
at least for the next
four years, and so there.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:52.880
But I think you can work with
cities very much so hoping

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:57.290
to bring about local legislation
that is in favor of that.

00:44:57.290 --> 00:44:58.730
And there's a
whole sort of list.

00:44:58.730 --> 00:45:00.271
I mean, I have in
fact even a slide--

00:45:00.271 --> 00:45:02.210
I can show it to
you afterwards--

00:45:02.210 --> 00:45:04.640
which lists the things
that we're proposing,

00:45:04.640 --> 00:45:09.220
like a revolving loan fund for
platforms co-ops town hall.

00:45:09.220 --> 00:45:14.920
Set up townhalls to
discuss these issues

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:17.380
and many other things.

00:45:17.380 --> 00:45:21.020
The problem with
American policy is

00:45:21.020 --> 00:45:24.780
that it's relatively
friendly to monopolies,

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.930
but it's really
hostile to cartels.

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:29.480
And something like
Mondragon, which is really

00:45:29.480 --> 00:45:32.530
a network of cooperatives, would
definitely be seen as a cartel

00:45:32.530 --> 00:45:35.040
and would not be tolerated.

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:39.280
So you have to find
ways to influence that,

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:41.735
as the people in Denver did.

00:45:41.735 --> 00:45:42.610
Thank you, everybody.

00:45:42.610 --> 00:45:48.060
[APPLAUSE]

